Your `formGroup` doesn&#39;t do anything here. To use reactive forms, see the examples in the [docs][1]. Here since you have used `ngModel` on the radio buttons, you can use it along with [`ngIf`][2] to conditionally display the `Compaign` or `Script` panels.
```html
&lt;!-- 1st panel of Compaign--&gt;
&lt;form class=&quot;example-form&quot; *ngIf=&quot;option === &#39;compaign&#39;&quot;&gt;
    &lt;!-- Compaign panel content goes here --&gt;
&lt;/form&gt;

&lt;!-- 2nd panel for script--&gt;
&lt;form class=&quot;example-form&quot; *ngIf=&quot;option === &#39;script&#39;&quot;&gt;
    &lt;!-- Script panel content goes here --&gt;
&lt;/form&gt;
```

where `compaign` and `script` are the values of your radio buttons respectively.

Here is a working example on [StackBlitz][3].


  [1]: https://angular.io/guide/reactive-forms
  [2]: https://angular.io/api/common/NgIf
  [3]: https://stackblitz.com/edit/angular-radio-ng-if

